article.headline: Kansas State uses maturity to overcome Ball State

article.linkText: No. 5 Kansas State gets a scare, but holds off Ball State
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Kansas State coach Deb Patterson is just
glad her team didn't panic.

<photo1>

	   Ball State had Patterson and the rest of the fifth-ranked
Wildcats worried Friday night, after the Cardinals outhustled
Kansas State to lead by as many as eight points in the first half.
But Kansas State rallied for a 71-61 victory in the first round of
the preseason WNIT.

	   Patterson attributed the victory to maturity and resiliency. Of
course, having three players reach double figures in scoring and
rebounding didn't hurt.

	   Kendra Wecker had 20 points and 12 rebounds, Nicole Ohlde had 18
points and 16 rebounds, and Brie Madden added 10 points and 11
rebounds for the Wildcats (1-0).

	   ''I felt it was difficult all night long for us to get into a
rhythm offensively,'' Patterson said. ''It took a lot of growth for
our team to not panic. Ball State had nothing to lose. I bet our
players were sensing that, 'Boy, we have a lot to lose.' I was
proud of them.''

	   Johna Goff hit five 3-pointers and scored 23 to lead Ball State
(0-1). Tamara Bowie had 15 points and 10 rebounds, and Kate Endress
scored 15.

	   In the second round Sunday, Kansas State will play Georgia Tech,
which defeated North Carolina-Charlotte 67-57.

	   Bowie scored seven points during a 14-0 run in the first half to
give the Cardinals an eight-point lead with 3:24 left in the game.

	   ''We were all just too excited,'' Ohlde said. ''We just kind of
had to get the kinks out, and we were doing that the whole game.''

	   Kansas State used a late flurry to get to 34-31 at halftime.

	   ''I was extremely proud of our team's execution,'' Ball State
coach Tracy Roller. ''They're a darned good team, and we had to
execute our game plan down to the wire. I thought we handled it
very well.''

	   Kansas State went on an 8-0 run in the second half to go ahead
by six.

	   Ball State rallied, as Goff and Endress tied the game with 10
minutes to go with back-to-back 3s. The Cardinals stayed close
until Laurie Koehn scored six consecutive points in the final four
minutes, giving Kansas State an eight-point lead with 24.7 seconds
left and securing its fourth consecutive season-opening victory.

	   ''The only way to stop her is to keep the ball out of her
hands,'' Roller said of Koehn. ''But good players step up at good
times.''

	   Ball State shot just 32 percent in the first half but forced 11
turnovers by the Wildcats. Kansas state outrebounded the Cardinals
57-39.

	   ''At halftime, we talked about defending and rebounding the
ball,'' Wecker said. ''We wanted to come out and put a body on
them.''
